The easiest solution here would be to use a MemoryStream to save the temporary pdf file while you are adding to it. After some research I&#39;ve found that as mkl suggests the PdfStamper class is unsuited for this operation. In iTextSharp you can append 2 PDF&#39;s using another way:

            MemoryStream stream = new MemoryStream();
            PdfCopyFields copy = new PdfCopyFields(stream);


            var ms1 = new MemoryStream(File.ReadAllBytes(file1Path));
            ms1.Position = 0;
            copy.AddDocument(new PdfReader(ms1));
            ms1.Dispose();

            var ms2 = new MemoryStream(File.ReadAllBytes(file2Path));
            ms2.Position = 0;
            copy.AddDocument(new PdfReader(ms2));
            ms2.Dispose();
            copy.Close();

The resulting &#39;stream&#39; variable contains the combined PDF&#39;s and can be written to a file using the PdfStamper.

If switching to iText 7 for .net is an option, the PdfStamper can be omitted and PdfDocument.copyPagesTo() method can be used instead.

a simple example (With iText 7 for .net):

        MemoryStream stream = new MemoryStream();
        PdfDocument outputDocument = new PdfDocument(new PdfWriter(stream));
        PdfDocument pdfSource = new PdfDocument(new PdfReader(&quot;c:\\firstInput.pdf&quot;));

        pdfSource.CopyPagesTo(1, pdfSource.GetNumberOfPages(), outputDocument);
        pdfSource = new PdfDocument(new PdfReader(&quot;c:\\secondInput.pdf&quot;));
        pdfSource.CopyPagesTo(1, pdfSource.GetNumberOfPages(), outputDocument);
        pdfSource.Close();
        outputDocument.Close();

        MemoryStream outputStream = new MemoryStream(stream.ToArray());
        outputDocument = new PdfDocument(new PdfReader(outputStream), new PdfWriter(&quot;c:\\result.pdf&quot;));

